"Drage E.A., Jaksch D., Smith K.M., McPheat R.A., Vasekova E., Mason N.J.","FTIR spectroscopy and estimation of the global warming potential of CF3Br and C2F4",2006,"Journal of Quantitative Spectroscopy and Radiative Transfer","98","1",,"44","56",,,10.1016/j.jqsrt.2005.05.071,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-29244448700&partnerID=40&md5=5e17f9376942e26fc2402d040a471599","Department of Physics and Astronomy, Open University, Walton hall, Milton Keynes MK7 6AA, United Kingdom; Rutherford Appleton Laboratory, Space Science and Technology Department, Chilton, Didcot, Oxon. OX11 0QX, United Kingdom","Drage, E.A., Department of Physics and Astronomy, Open University, Walton hall, Milton Keynes MK7 6AA, United Kingdom; Jaksch, D., Department of Physics and Astronomy, Open University, Walton hall, Milton Keynes MK7 6AA, United Kingdom; Smith, K.M., Rutherford Appleton Laboratory, Space Science and Technology Department, Chilton, Didcot, Oxon. OX11 0QX, United Kingdom; McPheat, R.A., Rutherford Appleton Laboratory, Space Science and Technology Department, Chilton, Didcot, Oxon. OX11 0QX, United Kingdom; Vasekova, E., Department of Physics and Astronomy, Open University, Walton hall, Milton Keynes MK7 6AA, United Kingdom; Mason, N.J., Department of Physics and Astronomy, Open University, Walton hall, Milton Keynes MK7 6AA, United Kingdom","High-resolution (0.03 cm-1) absolute infrared photoabsorption cross sections of bromotrifluoromethane (CF3Br) and tetrafluoroethylene (C2F4) have been measured using Fourier-transformed infrared (FTIR) spectroscopy at temperatures between 213 and 296 K. The measured cross sections were subsequently used to estimate the radiative forcings and the global warming potentials of these two species. © 2005 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","C2F4; CF3Br; FTIR; Global warming; Infrared spectroscopy","Absorption spectroscopy; Atmospheric radiation; Fluorocarbons; Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy; Global warming; Heat trans